As Dawn wrote to Dr. Math
On 09/21/2004 at 17:32:06 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>The sum of three consecutive odd integers is the same as five times 
>the greatest of these integers.
>
>[Difficulty]
>I am having a hard time putting the words into an equation to solve.
>
>[Thoughts]
>x+(x+2)+(x+4)=5(x+4)
>3x+6=5x+20
>3x=5x+14
>-2x=14
>x=-7

Looks great to me, Dawn!
The next step would be to check.
If x = -7, then the three integers are -7, -5, and -3, so the sum is -15,
which indeed is five times the greatest of the integers, -3.

So it works.  Good job!


